<UserId.>100746719456158037107</UserId.>< username>
Christine Gee</username>
< Review>
I always get a basic mani before doing any kind other services at any nail salon so that I can observe the technicians habits, cleaniness, and general service.

Queenie's is known for nail art and there is definitely not denying it's really well done and beautiful. They do gel, acrylic, and shellac. Also even on a weekday (Wends.) they had at least 20 technicians on hand who mostly were all busy with a customer. So definitely make an appointment if you can or expect to be waiting a while.

My techs name was Evan and she was nice but mostly stayed focused on my mani which is always a +. The only thing that threw me was how dirty her nails where :( and it's not the typical nail polish under the nails kind of messy that is common with nail techs. Hers we're actually dirty and it was really off putting. The only saving grace was that Queenie's overall is a 100% on cleaniness from what I observed (each customer gets their own sanitized tool pack and files, pedi stations were cleaned out properly after each use). But basically since all the tools she was using were clean it didn't bother me too much plus what would I say?

Cuticle work and nail filing was good but she didn't ask me what shape I wanted for my nails and automatically did square which was fine but I wish I had been asked. The other not such a big deal but still I wish I had been given the option is nail color choice. I was given 1 pallette of colors to choose from and while it was a variety the customer next to me got 3 different color pallette options however this might have to do with type of service given I was doing a basic mani while most do gel, shellac, or acrylics.

Quality of work so far is quite good. My nails are going strong 3 days later with regular use (dishes, typing, gym, etc).

I paid $25 for the elite mani which comes with collogen gloves, massage, and the other basic services.

*NOTE: CASH ONLY*

So not a perfect experience but nothing serious. I would definitely go back and try out more services.</Review>

<review>Consider the following:
My wife and I have been coming here for the past decade.
I bring everyone that comes to visit me here to demonstrate San Diego Mexican food.
I brought my brother here once, and he recently asked me to bring him a burrito from this shop. He lives 500 miles away.

The quality of the food is beyond reproach, and has been for 10 years. I recommend the surf and turf burritos, the surf and turf fries, the shrimp tacos, and everything else on the menu. When you go in, grab a cup of the water out of the jug to the left. Its amazing.< /review>< resp>

<date>1492565254326<//date>< Rate>
3</Rate>
< Review>
Their prices are reasonable, they're in a central location which makes it the perfect place to grab something to eat while you're in PB after hours. They don't sell water I guess and you have to pour your own water out of a Gatorade keg. They don't offer you salsa to go but you are also more than welcome to package some up for yourself. The staff are nice, they're just what you want out of a Mexican restaurant in the evening @ pacific beach.</Review>

I have been 3 times since moving to be PB (1 Month total). This place is great and the staff are friendly, honest, and accomedating. Food is clean, tasty, and well prepared for an awesome price. Parking is a challenge, but since when is parking not a challenge in Pacific Beach? Ha ha

< text>
To note is a particularly unique shrimp burrito. Almost a sealed shrimp fajita, lacking beans, lacking rice. Grilled shrimp, onion, tomato, and sour cream. A thick, saucy vegetable-and-shrimp burrito that heavily delivers its wares and is deceptively - yet gratuitously- filling.< /text>

<response>None< /response><Rate>5</Rate>< text>
Stopped while driving by because it looked like a legit, small time taco place. Glad I did because they were doing $.99 Tuesday TJ street tacos. Generous helpings of meat and guacamole, no rice or bean filler. Good corn tortillas. Carne asada was cooked just right, where it's still tender but has a little crispy-ness to the outside. Chips were warm and fresh, salsa was good. Will be going back.</text>

I remember the days when the Exploratorium was located at the Palace of Fine Arts. With the move to this location along the Embarcadero, I haven't had a chance to visit this new facility until recently when I went to "Exploratorium After Dark" on Thursday nights from 6-10pm. Avoid the long lines and assure entry by buying your tickets online before 5pm and save $2 too.< /review>

<Name>Ambrielle Army</Name>< Gmap_id>
0x80c2c7b4e31a2fe1:0xc5bd0edb9c8feea3<//Gmap_id>
<Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNdaPf-pUsVXkpdwPM-NinrQAiZWQ2p5l4rJWv0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNzRzKp5J8OyMnFqIdRWWnHkYsBMKYh4N6tPgdT=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>< user_id>
102075488447917046515</user_id>
< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Review>
Finally got around to visiting Cicada Club and it far exceeded my expectations! An evening here will run you a fair bill (dining prix fixe is $59 per person plus the $25 entry and pricey drinks) but is well worth it.  You must reserve a table and eat to have guaranteed seating, which we did - but there looked to be ample seating room with couches in the bar and lounge area.

The venue and decor are exceptional, with amazing art deco wall to wall. The dress code means that everyone will be dressed to the nines and many in vintage looks, so you'll feel truly transported to another era.

The music was amazing - it rotates but we got to see an incredible big band.  There dance performances as well, which made for a fun and lively evening (not to mention the dance floor constantly hopping with guests).

The food really surprised me. I expected it to be average because the club is so experience focused, but it was actually very good. I tried the seared scallop, almond salmon, crab linguine (special), tirimusu, chocolate cake, and apple tart as we were all sharing a bit. Everything except the chocolate cake was memorable, particularly the scallop and salmon.  The chocolate cake was the only thing that left something to be desired, mostly just a dry brownie.

Overall, Cicada Club should definitely be on your list. You'll be hard pressed to find another place where everyone there is so enthusiastic about embracing the evening and having a great time. Strongly recommend!</Review>
<time>1556442713967< /time>< response>
{'time': 1556932027028, 'text': 'Thank you Ambrielle for the lovely post.  I will make sure to let the pastry chef know about the chocolate cake.  I apologize for that.  We look forward to seeing you again. Richard Liberman'}< /response>

< Review>
Do you like big bands? Do you like live music? Do you like the bygone era of the 30s, 40s, and 50s? Then Cicada Club is the place you want to be. Grab your top hat and tuxedo or your sequined dress and go have a blast. Once you walk through the doors you are swept away back in time. From the sparkling chandeliers, to the imported marble and hand carved wood pillars this place is a visual delight. There is a different band placing each weekend. And plenty of ballroom dancing. The food is outstanding and the bar is extensive. Grab your favorite somebody and treat yourself.<//Review>

< Review>
The only reason I'm giving this 4 out of 5 stars is that I find the wine list to be outrageously expensive, the lowest price bottle of cabernet sauvignon is $80.
Bottles of other wines/champagnes are also marked up 300% or so.
That said, the ambiance and experience is fabulous!! The 3 course meal is $59 whether you have a vegetarian meal or not and we enjoyed the food. Service was good, not great. and I love to dress up and see everyone else who dresses up as well. I think you'll really enjoy this place, just bring lots of $$.< /Review>

<Rating>1<//Rating>< Review>
The night was beyond disappointing. I bought tickets and made a reservation weeks in advance for my boyfriend's birthday. We were seated at a table where one of the seats faced away from the stage and the band but when we politely asked permission to rotate the chair, they never got back to us. Our waiter, William, ignored us most of the night, avoided eye contact, and never checked on us. He seemed very eager to take our check though and have us leave, as he stopped by our table 3 times within 15 minutes after we got our bill. That was by far the most attention he gave us during the whole evening. As an avid member of the swing dancing community and a follower of the Los Angeles Art Deco Society, I would not recommend going here for any kind of special occasion or nice evening. But a big thank you to the lovely hostesses who were helpful and kind to us.< /Review>

< Review>
The ambience and venue are absolutely breathtaking - making for a wonderful girl's night. Although, it definitely would be great for date night or anniversary dinner. The food delectable, every dish description made my mouth water - will return to try more. The Fettucine Filet Mignon Ragout was amazing! Everyone loved the nine-pepper new york steak. My favorite was the cocktail list -creative, delicious and affordable. They serve the classics - Manhattan (my fav) and Sazerac - to your more creative Bee's Knees and Penicillin. Service was on point - attentive, friendly and well-timed! Valet parking is available, in addition to the pay structures in the area.</Review>

<rate>5< /rate>< text>
Truly magical experience! A time-capsule that takes you back to the era that F. Scott Fitzgerald invoked in "The Great Gatsby." Men dressed to the nines with their 3-piece suits and fedoras, women dressed like goddesses in their flapper dresses. What's not to love. Came through with a group of 8 for a birthday party and were very impressed with the entertainment supplied. A band ripped and rolled through a selection of jazz standards that had everyone swing-dancing and slow-dancing the night away. The bar can be a tad on the slow side concocting your drinks but other then that this place is a sure fire winner for any of those who are looking to have a classy evening on the town.<//text>

<gmap_id>0x80c2c7b4e31a2fe1:0xc5bd0edb9c8feea3< /gmap_id>< Text>
When you go downtown LA and you see all the old buildings, you wonder what it must have been like in the old days.  I understand for you Easterners and Europeans, 80 years ago isn't all that long ago.  But here in SoCal that was a while ago.  When you walk into Cicada you are taken back to the 20s or 30s and you see what what intricate workmanship looks like.  It's a delight to be there.  The food was good and the service terrific.  You have to stop by sometime to enjoy a complete experience of yester-year.   Oh and the music is often incredible and from the old days also.<//Text>

5< /rate>
< name>
Hanae K</name>
<userid>102191991550028128685< /userid><text>The closest Gatsby-esque moment I've experienced. Stunning ladies in their flapper attire being twirled around by gents sporting a bow-tie on a Sunday night. Live 20s band singing, playing the piano, dancing, etc. That feeling that you're in another era was priceless. Right when you walk in you wouldn't believe that this is in downtown LA.

You don't have to pay for dinner to enjoy this. Sunday nights (with cover) they'll have live music and a lounge upstairs in the back to rest your feet after hours of swing dancing.

DINNER: we got a great seat with an amazing server. It's a one table per night seating (so the table is all yours that whole night). Food was decent, the risotto was my favorite. Alcohol was ok. You're paying for the experience and the great service. Evertime we stood up to explore/take pics/dance, we saw the server refold our napkin. I've only seen people do that at club33 and CUT.

If you still want to enjoy the 20s after dinner, I recommend walking over to Varnish. They have live 1920s music as well.

R.Gadget suggested this place to my bf. Thanks Gadget!!!< /text><Gmap_id>0x80c2c7b4e31a2fe1:0xc5bd0edb9c8feea3< /Gmap_id><Pics>None<//Pics><Date>1398196265978<//Date><resp>None<//resp></record>

I leave this review because I was surprised, shocked and bemused at this establishment. Very cute shop that says crepes on cannery row, so we came in and ordered a savory crepe. 20 mins go by and the order does not come through. I'm seeing both the workers on the other side not doing much but just moving around. I finally go up to the counter to ask for my order and the server gives me this surprised look, "your order?" and looks at the receipt and says, " oh he (as in the guy making the crepes) didn't make it". I'm sorry, but what? There were like 3 people in the restaurant at the time and mine was the last order. I got my money back including the tip when I asked the order to be cancelled but really, how can you let this happen on a weekend when the area is bustling? Maybe that's why this place was not as full as the other restaurants?<//text>

< text>
CaliK9 is a great facility and Jas has a good team of trainers (himself included obviously) that pretty much takes care of everything. I had purchased the 20/20 training package for my German Shepherd that I initially trained myself from when I got him at 11 weeks up until about 3years of age when I took him in to go with some more advanced work to certify him as a service dog and protection dog, and it's definitely worth it! Jas does great work and I really enjoyed the training, to be honest though they're not really just training your dog, they're training you to train your dog  and its all based on the dogs behavior, which is great is a pretty great tactic and it teaches you to understand your dog's behavior. My  the only reason I give 4 stars is because I feel his admin team should be more organized and stay top of tracking records or the emails they send out. I haven't finished all my training sessions nor have I heard back in over a year, but I also haven't followed up on a count of being very busy myself (bad excuse I know but life happens). Either way, if you consider wanting to get professional training, Jas has a long line of very credible work and has even trained dogs for some very famous celebrities and athlete's. I'm also very thankful for his guidance with my K9. And I'm long overdue for refreshers lol.< /text>

<rating>5< /rating><text>I've been bringing Marvin to Cali K9 for almost a year now, and he has come a long way. From a giant , rambunctious puppy, to a giant teenage dog, he's becoming a very good canine citizen.

<GmapID>0x808fccc2e30a1545:0x773c4e230de6ebf3<//GmapID>< Review>
In 2011, I was a veteran dog owner, but a real dog training novice when I decided to train my elderly pit bull at Cali K9's occasional weekend classes in the Oakland Hills and Fremont. I quickly discovered there's a lot more to it than the standard "sit, stay, down" drill. Jas and his team trained me, not just my dog. And I also earned from watching other dog owners interact with their dogs in such a balanced way.

It was up to me to practice the training techniques I learned and use them consistently. This experience changed what became my last weeks with my 15-year-old best friend. Sadly, she was slowly dying of cancer and I eventually had to put her down. Around that time, I was home alone and was caught up in a scary armed home invasion robbery, which cemented my decision to re-evaluate and beef up my home security and get another canine companion.

A client of California K9 Solutions knew about a young Doberman rescue dog that needed a forever home. He was big, beautiful and friendly, but completely untrained and "all over the place". At the time, it was impossible for me to walk him down the street. Cali K9 trained me and my 95 lb. wild teenager at their facility in San Jose so I could take him anywhere. The 15 minutes of practice once or twice a day paid off and now I'm able to walk him off leash and feel confident he'll listen to me. In addition, he's turned into an amazing security dog, so I feel totally safe in my home and neighborhood. This whole experience turned into one of the best things that's ever happened to me. From the bottom of my heart, thank you Jas and company!</Review>

I had both an excellent experience and excellent orthodontic outcome with Dr. Waldman and his team. I was told by numerous dentists and orthodontists that my bite problems (open bite) could only be corrected with surgery which would have been invasive and painful with a tough recovery and much lost time from work. I highly recommend Dr. Waldman and his team and if I had to make the decision over again I would do so without hesitation.< /Review>

< Review>
Dr. Waldman and his team are fantastic! This was the best money I ever spent! Although his services for Invisalign are on the pricier end, it's worth every single penny to choose his facility over others. Over the course of my 16 month treatment, I probably stepped into the office about 4 times? Each appointment was always on time and concise. The use of the Dental Monitoring System allowed the team to monitor my progress from home using a VR looking box designed for your mouth, lol. By having the DM app, the team signaled when to stay on the current tray or advance onto the next set of aligners- this was especially useful during the first round of closures during of pandemic because I still had access to the care I needed from the comfort of my home. Upon re-opening, the office made sure to take every safety measure possible in order to protect both patients and staff. The office is extremely accessible by app, text, or phone which is so convenient as a working adult! My friends and family are so impressed with how quickly and beautifully my teeth have shifted. Thank you Waldman Ortho!</Review>

Dr. Waldman and his entire staff are top notch!  They are such "people persons" who care about and understand kids and families and everyone's concerns.

Our pediatric dentist, Dr. Nikfarjam (who is also fantastic, by the way) recommended Dr. Waldman to us.  I was skeptical because they work right down the hall from each other, and I wasn't sure I wanted to go to an orthodontist that just seemed convenient.  It turns out that Dr. Waldman is simply the best, nicest and most knowledgeable person and doctor.  (My own father was a dentist, so I can get kind of picky about who touches our teeth!)  I think he received his MD from Harvard - so he's obviously smart.  But he explains things in a way that makes sense to "common people" and he never seems rushed or that he's just trying to work through his schedule.  His associates are also wonderful, warm, knowledgeable and professional.  Although going to the orthodontist isn't everyone's favorite thing to do, my son never resisted going to see Dr. Waldman.  To me, the fact that Dr. Waldman has one of those really expensive low/no radiation 3-D scanners speaks volumes about his priorities - he spends money on equipment that won't harm kids - even if it means lower margins for him.

Most importantly, my son started out with the craziest and most crooked teeth possible - and now has beautifully straight teeth.  In fact - he just said that one of the things he likes about himself are his "nice teeth!"</text>

<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
It's rare I give 5 stars but it was well earned today everybody woz wonderfully respectful kind and considerate as well as professional. From giving me the address over the phone, text reminders, to accommodating me because there was an accident and I was running a bit late. The staff was welcoming when I got there, easygoing and easy to deal with and helpful.  The technician conducting my scans also was professional polite and cared about my comfort and getting the tests done as quickly as possible and accurately as possible and provided me a disc. At the end of the day equally important was validation for parking making the total visit quite easy. Many years ago I came here and it was not a good experience today was a complete 100% turnaround I highly recommend this location for your X-ray CT and MRI needs.< /review>

Great experience. Friendly staff. Covid-19 safety protocols in place.  Filled out the paperwork then I was taken to the back to change.  Comfortable gown that wraps around so you don't have to tie them or feel exposed.  Changing area with lockers and shutter doors not curtains.  A small sofa to sit and wait for them to come and get you.  Friendly techs.  When done I requested a copy of my images and the front desk put them on a CD for me.  I was also able to make my appointment online. They also had openings for an earlier day and they called to see if I wanted to do the MRI sooner.  They have a parking structure, but I parked at a parking meter.  So I can not say anything about the parking; if they charge, validate, or the cost to park their.</Text>

<review>This facility was outstanding!
I had a PET scan this morning (the first appointment, arriving just before 6 am), and as far as scans go (and I've had them all...multiple times...due to metastatic breast cancer...so I know what I'm talking about), this was practically a spa day!
Shiran was my technician, and she couldn't have been nicer!
I was treated with kindness and respect, my needs were met, my pain and physical discomfort was considered. Even the injection wasn't so bad (and trust me, I have one arm that can't be used due to lymph node extraction, and the "good" arm has pretty fried veins from chemo). Shiran was gentle, and calm, and made me feel really comfortable while I went through the steps to prepare for the scan.
She made sure I was warm and comfortable while lying down for the scan (not the easiest since I have a lot of complications that make comfort hard to come by), and practically swaddled me like a baby.
It was up to me to just breathe, and lie as still as I could, but she made everything else quite easy.
Thank you Shiran!!!

<text>I'm used to reviewing restaurants more than imaging centers , but they asked me to so here we go: parking's expensive $20 Max I found a place on the street and then lo and behold they offered to validate my parking. The waits are a little bit long so I had time to move my car and save a few bucks.
The facility is beautiful and professional. Lots of colored glass, stone and wood highlights,  very nicely done and very clean. It's something you would expect in Beverly Hills.
After checking in and getting your background paperwork done you'll need to be patient. This place is an Imaging Factory. Not in a bad way, but in an efficient and professional way. Everybody there knows what they're doing and has a job to get done. I was there for a cat-scan and had three different technicians who were all excellent and very knowledgeable about their craft. I was in and out in 10 minutes once I got to the machine and out the door in another 15 (only because I waited for my copy of the scan). If you get assigned to this center you're in good hands, it's American medicine at its best. Enjoy

I was sent here from my doctors office which is an hour away. They said it was going to be a 45 min wait for an X-ray but it turned out to be 3hrs. Parking around here is terrible. In pain and in the waiting room though, I saw the bigger picture:

They had a slide show on all the TV‚Äôs spouting the benefits of privitized imaging centers VS in-hospital imaging centers... the only benefit is cost, but since I‚Äôm on Medicare, I (thankfully) didn‚Äôt have to pay, thus, I only saw the negatives. As we know, there needs to be an overhaul of the medical industry here in America. After my experience, I now know privatized imaging centers are not apart of the answer. Please... more in-hospital imaging centers.< /review>

< Review>
My family member had a PET scan here today. VERY good experience with the technician - Lawrence Abrams - who was very attentive, kind and communicative.

They validate parking which is a plus in my books.

I only have 2 complaints:

(1) we weren‚Äôt given clear directions on how to find the parking entrance - which is on the south side of Wilshire on a quiet dead end street - so we had to drive around the block a few times In busy morning traffic before we figured it out.

(2)  they should have some form of distracting entertainment for the patients - there are TV screens, but they just have frozen medical ads on them.
